rComments: Different than your typical Psychology courses at UTM. He makes you think and question everything. Very sweet and approachable. Tests are fair. : ):)

Did you know that psychiatry actually has nothing to do with the brain? This class made me look at psychology and psychiatry in a whole different way. There are no absolutes. The lectures are very philosophical, but very engaging. He's the sweetest professor, he wants everyone to do well. His tests are more than fair, even if you're a slacker.

don't be fooled by the textbook. ALL PHILOSOPHY. watching the faces of psychology students as they finish and leave a philosophy professors midterm, priceless. I spent half the time deciphering the MEANING of the question and asking my self WHY and WHAT IF than summoning A-N-Y psychological information out of my brain at all. You've been warned!!!

The content I loved but he made it sometimes really boring. In the beginning, DON'T expect any psychology, it's all philosophy (mind-body problem) over and over again. Later though it becomes psychiatry and pharmacology. You have to stick with the mindset of no absolutes for everything otherwise you'll fail. Book is small but really easy.
nice to have someone talk about reality once in a while

There are no absolutes.  If you believe in biology, you absolutely can't believe in free will.  Dualism or Parallelism, which do you prefer?  Sound like a psychology course to you?  Did you know the DSM only looks at behaviour?  But hey, we did learn what a neuron was by the last class.  The textbook was good at least.
Boring classes (although its nice that he really cares about what he's teaching), but really easy tests.
